{
  "answer": "**In the Nāradasmṛti (Chapter 1, Mātṛkā 1), the text introduces legal procedure (vyavahāra) as having \"eighteen topics\" (aṣṭādaśa prakaraṇāni), which are the foundational \"titles of law\" (or categories of litigation).**[^1]\n\n**These eighteen titles are enumerated across verses M1.16–19 as follows:**\n\n1. Non-payment of debt  \n2. Deposits  \n3. Partnership  \n4. Resumption of a gift  \n5. Refusal to render service after agreeing to it  \n6. Non-payment of wages  \n7. Sale by one who is not the owner  \n8. Non-delivery of a sold article  \n9. Rescission of a purchase  \n10. Breach of an agreement  \n11. Disputes concerning land  \n12. The relationship between man and woman  \n13. Inheritance  \n14. Crimes of violence  \n15. Verbal assault  \n16. Physical assault  \n17. Gambling  \n18. Miscellaneous matters[^2]\n\n**The text notes that these eighteen topics further subdivide into 108 branches, due to the \"variety of human actions,\" with legal procedure having \"a hundred branches\" in total.**[^3] **Detailed rules governing each title follow in the subsequent sections (e.g., sections 1–18 under \"The Topics of Litigation\"), covering procedures, evidence, punishments, and resolutions specific to each category.**[^4]\n\n[^1]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-79e060).  \n[^2]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-99f176) (M1.16–19).  \n[^3]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-c6777e).  \n[^4]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [whole chapter](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/).",
